There are currently several treatments available for Ebola virus disease:
1. Antiviral therapy with antisense drugs such as ex Ol:Ebola and GS-5734
2. Monoclonal antibodies like ZMapp, REGN-EB3, and rituximab: These antibodies attached to specific Ebola proteins and causes the body immune system to take action
3. Plasma therapy: Patients receive frozen plasma from survivors or convalescent plasma from patients who have been successfully treated: This method proven to be less effective than monoclonal antibodies
4. Interferons and interleukins: These drugs are proteins that activate the immune system and they have been shown to increase survival rates in animal models
5. Stem Cells therapy: Two clinical trials have started in the Democratic Republic of the Congo to test the use of mesenchymal stem cells and umbilical cord blood-derived multi- Lineage Progenitor Cells.
6. Vaccines: Many vaccines have been developed and have recently been shown to be highly effective in preventing the disease

It is also worth noting that early management of the disease which includes hydration, early treatment of any secondary infections and management of the patients' organs should also be done along with any other treatments to improve the overall outcomes.

It's very important to note that Ebola is a very complex disease and every patient should be evaluated and managed based on their specific situation, comorbidities and other health factors by a healthcare professional.
